## Current limitations:

Several o1js limitations lead to those errors:

### 32-bit addressing space

Compiling and proving happens in 32-bit space. Given that prover keys generated during compilation can be as large as 1GB per contract, and with 32-bit, we can only address 4GB, the memory is running low very fast with the additions of new methods or contracts.

### Requirement to compile and have prover keys of the contract used only for verification. For example, if you have the method:

```typescript
export class NFT extends SmartContract {
  @state(Field) root = State<Field>();

  @method verify(proof: NFTMapStateProof) {
    const root: Field = this.root.get();
    this.root.assertEquals(root);
    proof.publicInput.root.assertEquals(root);

    proof.verify();
  }
```

that only verifies the proof of ZKProgram, and we know that we need only the verification key for the verification of the proof, nevertheless the compilation and prover keys of the ZKProgram are required in the current o1js version to compile this NFT contract.

### No possibility to dynamically save, load, and purge prover keys.

If we have 5 contracts referencing each other, the ability to keep in memory only the prover keys used right now and off-load other keys is not present in the current version of o1js.
Although, we should have the possibility to cache prover keys quite soon.

### There is no possibility to keep the prover keys of several contracts in separate 32-bit spaces.

All computers are now 64-bit, and having several 32-bit spaces managed by a 64-bit controller can help.

### Memory leaks

When using in the server environment, a memory leaks can lead to those errors

### The number of constraints is not a limitation

It should also be noted that the number of constraints that frequently is a limitation while using the Circom library usually is not a limitation with o1js that has a limit of 2\*\*16=65536 constraints.

## Using Proxy contract

Although all those limitations will definitely be lifted in the next versions of o1js, we need a way to compile the large contracts right now.

I would propose the following solution that allows the split of the large contract into several contracts that can be compiled independently:

1. Proxy contract that holds the root of the MerkleTree of implementation contract’s addresses (public keys)
2. State contracts (yes, there can be several contracts to have an on-chain state larger than 8 Fields). They do not have methods except for the update state method.
3. Implementation contracts with methods but without the state (their state is just the mirror of the State contract state).

The State contract has the @method update that checks the proof and updates the state from the implementation contract:

```typescript
export class StateContract extends SmartContract {
  @state(Field) state1 = State<Field>();

  @method update(implementationAddress: PublicKey, proof: ProxyProof) {
    // Check the proxy proof, confirming that
    // implementation contract address is included
    // in the Proxy MerkleTree
    proof.verify();

    // Check that root of implementations contracts MerkleTree is valid
    const proxy = new ProxyContract(PublicKey.PublicKey.fromBase58(
      “Proxy Contract Address”

    );
    proof.publicInput.root.assertEquals(proxy.root.get());
    implementationAddress.assertEquals(proof.publicInput.implementation);

    // Set new state
    const implementation = new Implementation(implementationAddress);
    const newState1 = implementation.state1.get());
    this.state1.set(newState1);

  }
```

The Implementation contract does all the business logic:

```typescript
export class Implementation extends SmartContract {
  @state(Field) state1 = State<Field>();

  @method myBusinessLogic(state1: Field, …) {
    // Check that the initial state is the same
    const state = new StateContract(PublicKey.PublicKey.fromBase58(
      “State Contract Address”
    );
    state1.assertsEqual(state.state1.get());

    // do some logic

    this.state1.set(newState1);
  }
```
